<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="406" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1446,1472]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
In external appearance, indistinguishable from most other members of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ribaut" authorityYear="1952" box="[1224,1377,1447,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1224,1377,1447,1473]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Macropsidius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Dlabola, 1961" authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1961" box="[260,536,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araxes">
<emphasis box="[260,371,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. araxes</emphasis>
Dlabola, 1961
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Dlabola, 1963" authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1963" box="[547,850,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valiturus">
<emphasis box="[547,684,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. valiturus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Dlabola, J." box="[689,850,1483,1509]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" pagination="114 - 124" refId="ref4366" refString="Dlabola, J. (1963) A revision of the leafhopper genus Macropsidius Rib. (Hom., Auchenorrhyncha). Acta Societatis Entomologicae Cehosloveniae, 60 (1 - 2), 114 - 124." type="journal article" year="1963">Dlabola, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[906,1043,1483,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kajkanus">
<emphasis box="[906,1043,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. kajkanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1057,1193,1483,1509]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838469" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Figs. 70–71</figureCitation>
), which also have one ventral and two lateral carinae on the aedeagus, in having very wide lateral carinae. In addition, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1961" box="[1238,1351,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="araxes">
<emphasis box="[1238,1351,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. araxes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlabola" authorityYear="1963" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valiturus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. valiturus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were recorded only from Eastern Caucasus (Dagestan), Transcaucasia, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1093,1141,1555,1581]" name="Iran" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Iran</collectingCountry>
, so their close relationship with species from 
<collectingCountry box="[360,491,1591,1617]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
is dubious. Very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[805,963,1591,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogutensis">
<emphasis box="[805,963,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. bogutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differing in the evenly curved ventral carina of the aedeagus almost reaching the gonopore (
<figureCitation box="[770,905,1626,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–18" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[171,1414,188,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-36@2.[165,1423,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–18. Macropsidius karatavicus sp. n. 1–2―male, dorsal view, 3―same, female, 4―male, face, 5―same, fe- male, 6–7―pygofer appendage, 8–10―penis, back view, 11–12―same, frontal and lateral view, 13–15―same, lateral view, 16–18―style." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838463/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Figs. 11–15</figureCitation>
) (strongly narrowed in apical half and usually almost reduced before gonopore in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[547,704,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogutensis">
<emphasis box="[547,704,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. bogutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<figureCitation box="[718,855,1662,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–62" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,185,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-36@6.[220,1368,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 34–62. Macropsidius bogutensis. 34–41―penis, back view, 42–45―same, frontal and lateral view, 46–54―same, lateral view, 55–62―pygofer appendage. 34, 42, 46, 55―paratype, 35, 43, 47, 56―male from the type locality, 36, 48, 57― drawings from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 37–40, 44–45, 49–53, 58–61―males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau Range (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 41, 54, 62―drawings from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838467" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838467/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Figs. 42–54</figureCitation>
). Also, distinctly differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mityaev" authorityYear="1990" box="[1190,1347,1663,1689]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Macropsidius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogutensis">
<emphasis box="[1190,1347,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">M. bogutensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in male calling signal pattern (
<figureCitation box="[401,664,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838465/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Figs. 19–23 and 24–28</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="406" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1735,1761]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Hosts.</emphasis>
Adult specimens were collected from 
<taxonomicName box="[714,986,1735,1761]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juncea" subGenus="Seriphidium">
<emphasis box="[714,739,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">A.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[756,893,1735,1761]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Seriphidium</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[911,986,1735,1760]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">juncea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on stony slopes (
<figureCitation box="[1188,1271,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 63–76" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1823,1847]" captionTargetBox="[223,1363,184,1795]" captionTargetId="figure-16@7.[223,1363,181,1799]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 63–76. 63―paratype of M. bogutensis, style, 64―same, male from the type locality, 65―same, drawing from the original description (after Mityaev, 1990), 66–68―same, males from Dzhungarskiy Alatau (M. zhuravlevi sensu Mityaev, 2014), 69―same, drawing from the original description of M. zhuravlevi (after Mityaev, 2014), 70―M. kajkanus, penis, back view, 71―same, frontal and lateral view, 72―same, lateral view, 73―distribution map of species of the M. bogutensis group, 74–76―biotopes,where insects were collected; localities, where photos were taken are shown with arrows, the whitish green plant in the center of each photo is Artemisia (Seriphidium) juncea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838469" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838469/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
) and were not found on other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[441,712,1771,1797]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Seriphidium">
<emphasis box="[441,550,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Artemisia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[566,703,1771,1797]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Seriphidium</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
growing nearby.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,371,1806,1832]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Calling signal.</emphasis>
Male calling signal is a short phrase lasting from 
<geoCoordinate box="[940,995,1806,1833]" degrees="2.5" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" precision="5555" value="-2.5">2.5 s</geoCoordinate>
, up to 8–9 s and consisting of 3–6 syllables in the recordings (
<figureCitation box="[434,574,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838465/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Figs. 19–23</figureCitation>
). Syllable consists of 11–18 similar pulses and has duration of 0.37– 
<geoCoordinate box="[1361,1431,1842,1869]" degrees="0.75" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" precision="555" value="-0.75">0.75 s</geoCoordinate>
. As a rule, pulse repetition period decreases towards the end of syllable. Occasionally, a train of pulses precedes or follows the sequence of syllables (
<figureCitation box="[537,621,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–33" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[223,1358,185,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-16@3.[214,1373,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 19–33. Macropsidius spp., calling signal oscillograms. 19–23―M. karatavicus sp. n., 24–28―M. bogutensis, 29– 33―M. kajkanus. Faster oscillograms of the parts of signals indicated as “21–22”, “26–28”, and “32–33” are given under the same numbers." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6838465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6838465/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1211,1950,1977]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,2013]" box="[199,1211,1950,1977]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1950,1976]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Distribution.</emphasis>
Possibly, endemic to Syrdaryinskiy Karatau Range in Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1072,1206,1951,1977]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1322,1987,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,798,2013]" box="[199,1322,1987,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1987,2013]" pageId="1" pageNumber="406">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name derives from the name of the mountain range, where it was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
